var tafsirData_43 = {
  1: {
    "Ḥâ-Mĩm": "These are among the disconnected letters (Huroof al-Muqatta'at) that appear at the beginning of some surahs. Their precise meaning is known only to Allah. However, scholars suggest they serve to capture attention and demonstrate that the Quran, though composed of familiar Arabic letters, is a miraculous composition that no human could replicate. These letters also highlight the inimitable nature of the Quran."
  },
  2: {
    "By the clear Book!": "Allah takes an oath by the Quran itself, emphasizing its importance and truthfulness. The Quran is described as 'clear' because it makes the truth evident, distinguishes right from wrong, and leaves no ambiguity for those who sincerely seek guidance. When Allah swears by something, it highlights its immense value and significance."
  },
  3: {
    "Certainly, We have made it a Quran in Arabic": "Allah chose to reveal the Quran in the Arabic language because it was the language of the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) and his people. Arabic is a rich, eloquent, and precise language capable of conveying deep meanings. This was so the first recipients—the Arabs—could understand it directly without any barrier of translation.",
    "so perhaps you will understand": "The purpose of revealing it in a clear, understandable language was so that people would comprehend its message, reflect upon its meanings, and apply its teachings in their lives. Allah wants guidance to be accessible, not hidden or confusing. This refutes any notion that religion should be mysterious or incomprehensible."
  },
  4: {
    "And indeed, it is—in the Master Record with Us": "The 'Master Record' (Umm al-Kitab) refers to the Preserved Tablet (Al-Lawh Al-Mahfuz), where Allah has recorded all divine decrees and scriptures. The Quran exists in this noble record with Allah, demonstrating that it is not a human invention but a divine revelation that has been preserved eternally in the heavens before being sent down to earth.",
    "highly esteemed, rich in wisdom": "The Quran holds an exalted status with Allah—it is honored, elevated above all other speech, and full of wisdom. Every verse contains profound guidance, solutions to human problems, and insights into the nature of existence. This description affirms that the Quran deserves the utmost respect and attention from humanity."
  },
  5: {
    "Should We then turn the Quranic Reminder away from you": "This is a rhetorical question highlighting Allah's mercy. Despite the people's rejection and disobedience, Allah continued to send them guidance. He did not withhold the Quran simply because they were ungrateful. This shows that Allah's mercy precedes His punishment—He gives people every opportunity to repent and return to the truth.",
    "simply because you have been a transgressing people?": "The term 'transgressing' refers to those who exceed all limits in sin, rebellion, and denial of the truth. Yet even such people are not immediately abandoned by Allah. He still sends them messengers and reminders, giving them chances to reform. This is a powerful demonstration of divine patience and compassion."
  },
  6: {
    "Imagine how many prophets We sent to those destroyed before!": "Allah reminds the Quraysh of Mecca that they are not unique in receiving a prophet. Throughout history, Allah sent countless prophets to various nations. The phrase 'how many' indicates a great number—from Adam to Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, and many others. This establishes that prophethood is Allah's consistent method of guiding humanity, and rejecting prophets has always led to severe consequences."
  },
  7: {
    "But no prophet ever came to them without being mocked": "This verse consoles the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) by showing him that mockery of prophets is nothing new. Every prophet before him faced ridicule from their people. Noah was mocked for building the ark, Abraham was ridiculed for rejecting idols, and Moses faced Pharaoh's arrogance. The pattern of disbelievers mocking prophets repeats throughout history, so the Prophet (ﷺ) should not be disheartened by the Quraysh's ridicule."
  },
  8: {
    "So We destroyed those who were far mightier than these Meccans": "Allah warns the Quraysh by reminding them that previous nations who rejected their prophets were far more powerful, wealthy, and technologically advanced than them—nations like 'Aad, Thamud, and the people of Pharaoh. Despite their power, they could not escape Allah's punishment when it came. The Quraysh, being weaker, should take this as a serious warning.",
    "The examples of their predecessors have already been related": "The stories of destroyed nations are preserved in the Quran as lessons and warnings. These are not mere tales but historical accounts meant to guide future generations. When one reads about the flood of Noah, the destruction of Sodom, or the drowning of Pharaoh, they should recognize the pattern: rejection of truth leads to ruin."
  },
  9: {
    "If you ask them O Prophet who created the heavens and the earth": "This verse exposes the inconsistency in the beliefs of the Meccan pagans. When directly questioned about the Creator of the universe, they would acknowledge Allah as the Creator. They did not attribute creation to their idols. This admission is significant—it shows that deep down, they recognized Allah's supreme power.",
    "they will certainly say, 'The Almighty, All-Knowing did.'": "Even the polytheists admitted that Allah alone possesses ultimate might (Al-Aziz) and complete knowledge (Al-Alim). These attributes belong exclusively to Him. The irony is that despite acknowledging this, they still worshipped idols alongside Him. This verse challenges them: if you know Allah is the Creator, why do you associate partners with Him in worship?"
  },
  10: {
    "He is the One Who has laid out the earth for you": "Allah spread out the earth and made it stable and suitable for human habitation. Like a cradle (mahd) that provides comfort and security for a baby, the earth is perfectly designed to support human life—with the right atmosphere, temperature, and resources. This is not by accident but by divine design.",
    "and set in it pathways for you so that you may find your way": "Allah created natural pathways through mountains, valleys, and plains so that humans can travel, trade, and explore. These routes between cities and regions allow civilizations to connect and flourish. Beyond the physical meaning, this also alludes to spiritual guidance—Allah provides clear paths to find the truth."
  },
  11: {
    "And He is the One Who sends down rain from the sky in perfect measure": "Allah sends rain in precisely calculated amounts—not too much to cause flooding and destruction, nor too little to cause drought and famine. This balance demonstrates Allah's perfect wisdom and control over nature. Every drop of rain is measured and decreed by Him.",
    "with which We give life to a lifeless land": "When rain falls on dry, barren land, it transforms into a lush, green landscape teeming with plants and life. This observable phenomenon is mentioned as a sign of Allah's power to create and revive.",
    "And so will you be brought forth from the grave": "Just as Allah revives dead land with rain, He will resurrect humans from their graves on the Day of Judgment. This analogy makes resurrection relatable and logical—if Allah can bring life to dead earth, bringing humans back to life is certainly within His power. This addresses those who denied the resurrection."
  },
  12: {
    "And He is the One Who created all things in pairs": "Allah created everything in pairs—male and female among humans and animals, positive and negative in atoms, night and day, hot and cold, and so on. This pairing is a sign of Allah's creative wisdom and points to His oneness, as only the Creator is without pair or equal.",
    "and made for you ships and animals to ride": "Allah blessed humanity with means of transportation. Ships allow travel across vast oceans, facilitating trade and exploration. Animals like horses, camels, and donkeys serve as mounts on land. These are divine gifts that humans should recognize and be grateful for."
  },
  13: {
    "so that you may sit firmly on their backs": "Allah designed these modes of transport for human comfort and safety. A camel's back is shaped to carry riders, and ships are built to float and carry passengers. These designs allow stable, secure travel.",
    "and remember your Lord's blessings once you are settled on them": "When riding an animal or boarding a ship, a believer should reflect on Allah's favors. This moment of settling into travel is an opportunity for gratitude, recognizing that the ability to travel is a blessing not to be taken for granted.",
    "saying, 'Glory be to the One Who has subjected these for us, for we could have never done so on our own'": "This is the supplication (dua) taught by the Quran for when one begins a journey. It acknowledges that humans, despite their intelligence, could never have tamed wild animals or mastered the seas without Allah's will. A camel or horse could easily overpower a human, yet Allah made them subservient. This dua instills humility and gratitude. The Prophet (ﷺ) would recite this prayer when mounting for travel."
  },
  14: {
    "And surely to our Lord we will all return": "Every journey is a reminder of the ultimate journey—our return to Allah. Whether traveling for business, leisure, or migration, a believer remembers that life itself is a journey, and death is the final destination before meeting Allah. This phrase, included in the travel supplication, keeps believers mindful of the hereafter even during worldly activities."
  },
  15: {
    "Still the pagans have made some of His creation out to be a part of Him": "The Arab polytheists committed a grave error by claiming that the angels were Allah's daughters, thus attributing offspring to Him. By doing this, they essentially said that part of creation (angels) was a part of the Creator—a fundamental contradiction. Allah is the Creator of all things; nothing from His creation can be part of His divine essence.",
    "Indeed, humankind is clearly ungrateful": "This statement highlights the blatant ingratitude of those who attribute partners or children to Allah. After receiving countless blessings from Allah—life, sustenance, guidance—they repay Him with disbelief and false claims. Such ingratitude is not hidden but is open and obvious (mubeen)."
  },
  16: {
    "Has He taken angels as His daughters from what He created": "This is a rhetorical question exposing the absurdity of the pagan belief. The idea that Allah—the Supreme, Self-Sufficient Creator—would have daughters is illogical. Allah does not beget nor is He begotten. He is free from any need for offspring.",
    "and favoured you O pagans with sons?": "The pagans themselves preferred sons over daughters, considering daughters a source of shame. Yet they hypocritically attributed daughters to Allah while wanting sons for themselves. This verse exposes their contradictory thinking: they assigned to Allah what they themselves despised, while claiming the preferred choice for themselves."
  },
  17: {
    "Whenever one of them is given the good news of what they attribute to the Most Compassionate": "When a pagan man was told that his wife had given birth to a daughter—the very gender they attributed to Allah—his reaction was telling.",
    "his face grows gloomy, as he suppresses his rage": "Instead of joy, his face would darken with disappointment and shame. He would struggle to contain his anger and frustration. This cultural attitude was so severe that some would even bury their daughters alive out of shame (a practice Islam abolished). The verse asks: how can you attribute to Allah what you yourselves hate and consider shameful? This exposes the injustice and irrationality of their beliefs."
  },
  18: {
    "Do they attribute to Him those who are brought up in fineries and are not commanding in disputes?": "This verse references the stereotypical description the pagans had of women—raised with jewelry and adornments, and (in their biased view) unable to argue effectively or defend themselves in debate. The verse is not endorsing this stereotype but using the pagans' own flawed logic against them: you look down on daughters with such descriptions, yet you attribute them to Allah? The inconsistency is glaring. Note: Islam elevated the status of women and abolished such degrading attitudes."
  },
  19: {
    "Still they have labelled the angels, who are servants of the Most Compassionate, as female": "The pagans made a baseless claim that angels are female. Angels are honored servants of Allah, created from light, who obey Him completely. They have no gender in the human sense, and assigning them one is pure fabrication.",
    "Did they witness their creation?": "This powerful rhetorical question demands evidence. Were the pagans present when Allah created the angels? Did they observe the process? Of course not. They had no knowledge whatsoever about the nature of angels, yet they made definitive claims. This teaches us that speaking about unseen matters without divine revelation is impermissible.",
    "Their statement will be recorded, and they will be questioned!": "Every false claim and lie about Allah will be documented by the recording angels. On the Day of Judgment, these people will be held accountable and questioned about their fabrications. This is a stern warning that false speech about Allah has serious consequences."
  },
  20: {
    "And they argue, 'Had the Most Compassionate willed, we would have never worshipped them.'": "The pagans used a twisted argument to justify their idol worship. They claimed that since Allah allowed them to worship idols, He must have approved of it. This is a misuse of the concept of divine will. Allah allows humans free will to choose right or wrong—this permission does not mean approval. A criminal cannot argue that because Allah allowed him to steal, stealing must be acceptable.",
    "They have no knowledge in support of this claim": "Their argument had no basis in revelation, reason, or evidence. It was pure speculation and a convenient excuse to continue their wrongdoing.",
    "They do nothing but lie": "Their claim was not just ignorance but deliberate lying. They invented justifications to avoid accountability. This teaches us that making religious claims without proper knowledge is a serious matter."
  },
  21: {
    "Or have We given them a Book for proof, before this Quran, to which they are holding firm?": "This verse challenges the pagans to produce any divine scripture that supports their idol worship or their claims about Allah having daughters. They had no such book. Their entire religion was based on speculation, inherited traditions, and fabrications—not divine revelation. This question silences their argument, as they could produce no evidence."
  },
  22: {
    "In fact, they say, 'We found our forefathers following a particular way'": "Unable to provide evidence, the pagans fell back on their only argument: tradition. They simply did what their ancestors did, without questioning whether it was right or wrong.",
    "and we are following in their footsteps": "They claimed to be guided by following their ancestors. This is the fallacy of blind imitation—assuming that something is correct simply because previous generations practiced it. This mentality prevents growth, reform, and acceptance of truth when it comes. Islam teaches that truth must be followed regardless of what ancestors practiced."
  },
  23: {
    "Similarly, whenever We sent a warner to a society before you O Prophet": "The Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) is being consoled that this resistance is not unique to him. Every prophet faced the same obstacle.",
    "its spoiled elite would say, 'We found our forefathers following a particular way, and we are walking in their footsteps'": "The term 'spoiled elite' (mutrafoon) refers to those who were blessed with wealth and luxury, which made them arrogant and resistant to change. Throughout history, it was often the wealthy and powerful who most strongly opposed prophets because accepting the truth would threaten their status and require them to change. They used ancestral tradition as their defense, just like the Quraysh."
  },
  24: {
    "Each warner asked, 'Even if what I brought you is better guidance than what you found your forefathers practicing?'": "Every prophet challenged his people with this logical question: What if the new guidance is actually superior to your ancestral traditions? A reasonable person would evaluate the message based on its merit, not simply reject it because it differs from tradition.",
    "They replied, 'We totally reject whatever you have been sent with.'": "Despite the reasonable appeal, the response was outright rejection without consideration. Their minds were closed, their hearts sealed. They refused even to evaluate the message, demonstrating the danger of prejudice and blind loyalty to tradition over truth."
  },
  25: {
    "So We inflicted punishment upon them": "When these nations persisted in their rejection despite clear warnings and patient prophets, Allah's punishment came. This was divine justice after every opportunity for repentance was exhausted.",
    "See then what was the fate of the deniers!": "This is an invitation to reflect on history. The ruins of destroyed nations like 'Aad and Thamud could still be seen by the Arabs during the Prophet's time. Their fate serves as a permanent warning: denial of truth leads to destruction. The Quraysh are being warned that they could face the same end."
  },
  26: {
    "Remember, O Prophet, when Abraham declared to his father and his people": "Allah directs attention to Prophet Ibrahim (Abraham), who is highly revered by the Arabs as their ancestor. His example directly contradicts their argument about following forefathers.",
    "'I am totally free of whatever gods you worship'": "Ibrahim publicly and boldly disassociated himself from the idol worship of his father Azar and his entire community. Despite family pressure and societal norms, he refused to follow the religion of his ancestors because he recognized it was false. This is the opposite of blind following—this is principled conviction based on truth."
  },
  27: {
    "except the One Who originated me": "Ibrahim made one exception—he worshipped only the One who created him from nothing. He recognized Allah as his Creator and therefore his only Lord worthy of worship. This declaration of pure monotheism (Tawheed) was revolutionary in a society drowning in polytheism.",
    "and He will surely guide me": "Ibrahim expressed complete trust in Allah's guidance. He knew that by sincerely seeking the truth and rejecting falsehood, Allah would continue to guide him on the straight path. This trust was rewarded—Ibrahim became the leader of all monotheists and the father of prophets."
  },
  28: {
    "And he left this enduring declaration among his descendants": "Ibrahim's declaration of monotheism—'La ilaha illa Allah' (There is no god but Allah)—became a lasting legacy passed down through his descendants. This word of Tawheed continued through his sons Ismail and Ishaq, and through the line of prophets that followed.",
    "so they may always turn back to Allah": "The purpose of this enduring message was to ensure that future generations would always have a path back to pure monotheism. Whenever people strayed into polytheism, the call of Ibrahim would remind them to return to the worship of One God. The Quraysh, as descendants of Ibrahim through Ismail, had access to this legacy but abandoned it for idol worship. They are being reminded of their forefather's true religion."
  },
  29: {
    "In fact, I had allowed enjoyment for these Meccans and their forefathers": "Allah explains that He gave the people of Mecca and their ancestors a period of worldly enjoyment—prosperity, security, and comfort. This was not a sign of His approval of their ways but rather a test and an opportunity. Allah's giving of worldly blessings does not indicate His pleasure with disbelief.",
    "until the truth came to them along with a messenger making things clear": "This period of enjoyment continued until Allah sent them Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) with the Quran—the clear truth that distinguished right from wrong. Now they had no excuse. The truth had arrived with a messenger whose character, miracles, and message were all clear and evident."
  },
  30: {
    "But when the truth came to them, they said, 'This is magic'": "Instead of accepting the truth, the Quraysh dismissed it as magic or sorcery. They could not deny the Quran's powerful effect on hearts and its miraculous eloquence, so they attributed it to supernatural trickery rather than divine revelation. This was an attempt to explain away what they could not refute.",
    "and we totally reject it": "After labeling it magic, they declared their complete rejection. This was stubborn denial, not based on evidence or reason, but on arrogance and unwillingness to change their ways. They rejected without investigation, without pondering—simply because acceptance would require them to abandon their power, status, and ancestral practices."
  },
  31: {
    "And they exclaimed, 'If only this Quran was revealed to a great man from one of the two cities!'": "The pagans objected to Muhammad (ﷺ) being chosen as the prophet, suggesting the Quran should have been given to someone they considered more important—a wealthy, powerful leader from Mecca or Ta'if (the two cities). They named figures like Al-Walid ibn al-Mughira of Mecca or Urwa ibn Mas'ud of Ta'if. This objection revealed their misunderstanding of prophethood. They thought worldly status qualified someone for divine selection, when in reality, Allah chooses prophets based on their character, purity of heart, and fitness for the mission—qualities Muhammad (ﷺ) possessed in the highest degree."
  },
  32: {
    "Is it they who distribute your Lord's mercy?": "This rhetorical question puts the pagans in their place. Who are they to decide who receives prophethood? Prophethood is Allah's mercy, and He alone decides who is worthy of it. Humans have no authority to determine where divine gifts should go.",
    "We alone have distributed their very livelihood among them in this worldly life": "Allah reminds them that even their worldly provisions—their wealth, resources, and abilities—are distributed by Him, not earned purely by their own efforts. Some are rich, some poor; some strong, some weak. This distribution is by divine wisdom.",
    "and raised some of them in rank above others so that some may employ others in service": "Allah created diversity in human abilities and resources so that society can function. The wealthy need workers; the skilled need employers. This interdependence creates social cohesion. No one is completely self-sufficient. This system is by divine design, not random chance.",
    "But your Lord's mercy is far better than whatever wealth they amass": "The ultimate point: prophethood and divine guidance (Allah's mercy) are infinitely more valuable than all the wealth of this world. The pagans valued worldly status, but true honor comes from being chosen by Allah for His service. Muhammad (ﷺ) may not have been the wealthiest, but he received the greatest gift—prophethood and the Quran. This is what truly matters."
  },
  33: {
    "Were it not that people might be tempted to become one community of disbelievers": "Allah explains why He does not give all worldly wealth exclusively to disbelievers. If He did so, people would mistakenly assume that wealth indicates Allah's approval and love. Many would then abandon faith and become disbelievers just to attain worldly riches. Human nature is weak, and many are easily swayed by material allure. Allah, in His mercy, prevents this mass temptation by distributing wealth among both believers and disbelievers.",
    "We would have supplied the homes of only those who disbelieve in the Most Compassionate with silver roofs and silver stairways to ascend": "Allah describes the luxuries He could have given exclusively to disbelievers—homes with ceilings made of silver and grand staircases of silver to climb. These descriptions represent the pinnacle of worldly luxury. The point is profound: such wealth is so insignificant to Allah that He would give it entirely to those He is displeased with. This shows that worldly possessions have no value as indicators of divine favor."
  },
  34: {
    "as well as silver gates and thrones to recline on": "Continuing the description, Allah mentions silver doors for their homes and luxurious thrones upon which they could recline in comfort. Every element of their living space would be extravagant. Yet all of this combined is worthless in Allah's sight compared to faith and righteous deeds. This passage reframes how believers should view wealth—it is not a sign of success or divine pleasure."
  },
  35: {
    "and ornaments of gold": "Gold ornaments and decorations would adorn their lives. The word 'Zukhruf' (from which this surah takes its name) refers to gold and elaborate decorations. The surah is named after these ornaments to emphasize their ultimate worthlessness compared to eternal rewards.",
    "Yet all this is no more than a fleeting enjoyment in this worldly life": "Despite how impressive these luxuries sound, Allah dismisses them as merely temporary enjoyment. The world and everything in it will perish. No matter how much gold or silver one accumulates, it will all be left behind at death. The Prophet (ﷺ) said: 'If this world were worth even a mosquito's wing to Allah, He would not have given a disbeliever even a sip of water from it.' (Tirmidhi)",
    "But the Hereafter with your Lord is only for those mindful of Him": "The real prize—eternal Paradise—is reserved exclusively for the Muttaqeen (those who are conscious of Allah and guard themselves against sin). While disbelievers may enjoy temporary worldly pleasures, believers who remain patient and faithful will enjoy everlasting bliss. This is the ultimate success that cannot be compared to any worldly wealth."
  },
  36: {
    "And whoever turns a blind eye to the Reminder of the Most Compassionate": "When a person deliberately ignores or turns away from the Quran and the remembrance of Allah, they make a dangerous choice. The 'Reminder' refers to the Quran and all forms of divine guidance. 'Turning a blind eye' means willfully ignoring the truth despite being aware of it—choosing heedlessness over guidance.",
    "We place at the disposal of each a devilish one as their close associate": "As a consequence of this deliberate rejection, Allah assigns a devil (Shaytan) to become that person's constant companion. This is not a punishment from nowhere—it is the natural result of rejecting guidance. When someone closes the door to Allah's remembrance, they open the door to Satan's influence. The devil becomes their 'Qareen'—an intimate companion who is always with them, whispering and influencing their thoughts and actions."
  },
  37: {
    "who will certainly hinder them from the Right Way": "These devilish companions actively work to obstruct their human associates from the path of truth. They discourage good deeds, beautify sins, cast doubts about faith, and create barriers to guidance. Every step toward righteousness is met with whispers of discouragement.",
    "while they think they are rightly guided": "This is the most dangerous aspect—the person being misled believes they are actually on the right path. The devil's deception is so subtle and effective that the victim feels confident in their misguidance. They may even think they are more enlightened than believers. This is spiritual blindness at its worst—being lost while feeling certain you are found. The Prophet (ﷺ) warned about people who do evil thinking it is good."
  },
  38: {
    "But when such a person comes to Us": "On the Day of Judgment, when this misguided person stands before Allah, the reality of their situation becomes horrifyingly clear. The veil of deception is lifted, and they see their devil companion for what it truly was.",
    "one will say to their associate, 'I wish you were as distant from me as the east is from the west!'": "The person will desperately wish they had never been associated with this devil. They express a desire for the maximum possible distance—from east to west—representing complete separation. The companion they thought was their friend and advisor is now revealed as their destroyer.",
    "'What an evil associate you were!'": "This is a cry of regret and anger. The intimate friend who whispered sweet deceptions is now cursed. But this realization comes too late. The time for separation was in the worldly life; now they must face the consequences together. This teaches us to be extremely careful about whose influence we allow into our lives and minds."
  },
  39: {
    "It will be said to both, 'Since you all did wrong'": "Both the human and the devil will be addressed together. Both are guilty—the devil for misleading and the human for following. The human cannot escape blame by pointing to the devil, because they chose to follow.",
    "sharing in the punishment will be of no benefit to you this Day": "A profound truth is stated: sharing punishment does not reduce it. In worldly life, shared hardship can bring comfort—'misery loves company.' But in the Hereafter, having a partner in punishment provides absolutely no consolation. Each will experience the full weight of their torment. The presence of the devil who misled them will add to their anguish, not diminish it."
  },
  40: {
    "Can you make the deaf hear, or guide the blind or those clearly astray?": "Allah consoles His Prophet (ﷺ) with a rhetorical question. Those who stubbornly reject the truth have made themselves spiritually deaf and blind. They cannot hear guidance because they have blocked their ears; they cannot see the truth because they have shut their eyes. The Prophet (ﷺ) is not responsible for their guidance—he can only convey the message. This verse relieves the Prophet (ﷺ) of the burden of feeling he must convert everyone. His job is to deliver; guidance is from Allah alone."
  },
  41: {
    "Even if We take you away from this world": "Allah addresses the possibility of the Prophet (ﷺ) passing away before witnessing the punishment of the disbelievers. Death is a certainty for all humans, including the beloved Prophet (ﷺ).",
    "We will surely inflict punishment upon them": "Allah assures that even if the Prophet (ﷺ) does not live to see it, divine retribution will certainly come to those who rejected the message. Allah's justice will be served, whether in the Prophet's lifetime or after. The punishment is guaranteed; only its timing is in Allah's hands."
  },
  42: {
    "Or if We show you what We threaten them with": "Alternatively, Allah may allow the Prophet (ﷺ) to witness the punishment of the disbelievers during his lifetime. Indeed, this occurred at the Battle of Badr, where many leaders of the Quraysh who had mocked and persecuted the Prophet (ﷺ) were killed.",
    "We certainly have full power over them": "Either way—whether the Prophet (ﷺ) witnesses it or not—Allah has complete control and power over the disbelievers. They cannot escape His grasp. This reassures the Prophet (ﷺ) that Allah is fully capable of dealing with his enemies."
  },
  43: {
    "So hold firmly to what has been revealed to you O Prophet": "Regardless of how people respond—acceptance or rejection—the Prophet (ﷺ) is commanded to hold tightly to the Quran and divine revelation. This is his anchor, his source of strength, and his guide. The command applies to all believers: no matter what challenges arise, we must cling to the Quran.",
    "You are truly on the Straight Path": "Allah affirms that the Prophet (ﷺ) is on the correct path—the path of truth, the path leading to Allah's pleasure and Paradise. This affirmation provides certainty and confidence. When doubts arise from the opposition of disbelievers, this divine confirmation dispels them."
  },
  44: {
    "Surely this Quran is a glory for you and your people": "The Quran is described as a source of honor, remembrance, and glory for the Prophet (ﷺ) and his community—the Arabs initially, and by extension, all Muslims. Being entrusted with the final revelation is an immense honor. The Quran elevated the Arabs from a marginalized desert people to leaders of a global civilization.",
    "And you will all be questioned about it": "With honor comes responsibility. On the Day of Judgment, everyone will be asked about the Quran: Did you believe in it? Did you follow it? Did you convey it? This accountability applies to the Prophet (ﷺ), his companions, and every Muslim who receives this message. The Quran is not just for recitation but for implementation."
  },
  45: {
    "Ask the followers of the messengers that We already sent before you": "Allah invites a review of all previous revelations and prophetic teachings. The 'asking' refers to examining the scriptures of previous prophets or consulting the knowledgeable followers of previous religions.",
    "if We ever appointed other gods to be worshipped besides the Most Compassionate": "The question is rhetorical: Did any previous prophet—Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, or any other—ever teach the worship of multiple gods? The answer is a resounding no. Every single prophet brought the same core message: worship Allah alone. This proves that polytheism is a human deviation, not a divine teaching. The Quraysh's idol worship had no basis in any prophetic tradition."
  },
  46: {
    "Indeed, We sent Moses with Our signs to Pharaoh and his chiefs": "Allah introduces the story of Prophet Musa (Moses) as an example for the Quraysh. Musa was sent with clear miraculous signs to Pharaoh (Fir'awn)—the most powerful ruler of his time—and his elite council. The parallel is clear: just as Pharaoh rejected Moses, the Quraysh leaders were rejecting Muhammad (ﷺ).",
    "and he said: 'I am a messenger of the Lord of all worlds'": "Musa introduced himself with clarity and authority. He did not claim to be a god or seek personal power. He simply declared his role as a messenger from the Lord of all creation. This straightforward declaration challenged Pharaoh's claim to divinity and demanded a response."
  },
  47: {
    "But as soon as he came to them with Our signs, they laughed at them": "The response of Pharaoh's court was mockery and laughter. Instead of seriously examining the signs, they ridiculed them. This is a common pattern among arrogant disbelievers—they use humor and mockery to dismiss what they cannot refute. The Quraysh did the same with Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ), and this verse draws the parallel."
  },
  48: {
    "although every sign We showed them was greater than the one before": "Allah sent a succession of miracles through Musa, each more impressive than the last—the staff turning into a serpent, the hand glowing white, and then the series of plagues: locusts, lice, frogs, blood, and more. Each was meant to break their stubbornness, yet they persisted in denial.",
    "Ultimately, We seized them with torments so that they might return to the Right Path": "The purpose of these afflictions was not mere punishment but a call to repentance. Allah, in His mercy, gives multiple chances before final judgment. The escalating signs were opportunities for Pharaoh and his people to humble themselves and return to the truth."
  },
  49: {
    "Then they pleaded, 'O mighty magician! Pray to your Lord on our behalf'": "When the torments became unbearable, Pharaoh's people came begging to Musa for relief. Their address 'O magician' shows they still did not truly believe—they thought he was performing magic, not miracles. Yet desperation forced them to seek his help.",
    "by virtue of the covenant He made with you": "They acknowledged that Musa had a special connection with his Lord and that Allah had made promises to him. This admission contradicted their earlier mockery but came only under duress.",
    "We will certainly accept guidance": "They promised to accept guidance if the punishment was removed. These were empty promises made in desperation, not sincere commitments to faith."
  },
  50: {
    "But as soon as We removed the torments from them, they broke their promise": "The moment relief came, they returned to their old ways. This is a pattern of insincere people—they call upon Allah in hardship and forget Him in ease. Their promises meant nothing. This behavior is warned against in many places in the Quran. True faith is consistent, not just activated by crises."
  },
  51: {
    "And Pharaoh called out to his people, boasting, 'O my people! Am I not sovereign over Egypt'": "Pharaoh gathered his people and reminded them of his power and dominion. He ruled over Egypt—one of the mightiest civilizations of the ancient world. His arrogance was boundless as he pointed to his kingdom as proof of his greatness.",
    "as well as all these streams flowing at my feet? Can you not see?": "The Nile River and its tributaries flowed through Egypt, providing life-giving water to the land. Pharaoh claimed credit for this blessing, as if the rivers flowed by his command. His rhetorical question 'Can you not see?' was meant to overwhelm his people with his apparent greatness and make them dismiss Musa's message."
  },
  52: {
    "Am I not better than this nobody who can hardly express himself?": "Pharaoh mocked Musa by calling him insignificant and pointing to a speech impediment Musa had (which some scholars say was a slight difficulty in speaking, resulting from a childhood incident). Pharaoh used worldly standards—eloquence, wealth, power—to judge worthiness, completely missing that prophethood comes from Allah based on character and purity, not rhetorical skill or royal status."
  },
  53: {
    "Why then have no golden bracelets of kingship been granted to him": "Pharaoh questioned why Musa did not have the symbols of royalty—golden bracelets that indicated status among Egyptians. If Musa truly represented the Lord of the worlds, why was he not adorned like a king?",
    "or angels come with him as escorts!": "Pharaoh demanded to see angels accompanying Musa as proof of his mission. This objection mirrors what the Quraysh said about Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ)—demanding visible angels as escorts. Both Pharaoh and the Quraysh failed to understand that prophets are not measured by worldly pomp but by divine truth."
  },
  54: {
    "And so he fooled his people, and they obeyed him": "Pharaoh manipulated his people through propaganda and false arguments. He made them feel small and dependent on him. Despite witnessing clear signs, they chose to follow their king rather than the truth.",
    "They were truly a rebellious people": "The people share blame for their destruction. They were not innocent victims; they were willing followers who chose rebellion against divine truth. When leaders mislead and people willingly follow, both are accountable. This is a warning against blind obedience to corrupt authority."
  },
  55: {
    "So when they enraged Us, We inflicted punishment upon them": "When their rebellion, mockery, and oppression reached its peak and they exhausted all chances for repentance, Allah's anger was kindled. The term 'enraged Us' indicates they crossed every line and pushed beyond all limits of divine patience.",
    "drowning them all": "The punishment was drowning in the Red Sea as they pursued Musa and the Children of Israel. Pharaoh, who boasted of rivers flowing at his feet, was destroyed by water. His entire army perished with him. The very element he claimed to control became his grave."
  },
  56: {
    "And We made them an example and a lesson for those after them": "Pharaoh and his people became a permanent lesson in human history. Their story is preserved not just in the Quran but in historical memory worldwide. Their destruction serves as a warning to every tyrant and arrogant denier who comes after them. The Quraysh, hearing this story, should have recognized themselves and feared a similar fate."
  },
  57: {
    "When the son of Mary was cited as an example in argument, your people O Prophet broke into joyful applause": "When verses were revealed stating that all false gods worshipped besides Allah would be fuel for Hell, a Quraysh man (reportedly Ibn al-Ziba'ra) argued: 'The Christians worship Jesus—so is Jesus in Hell too?' The Quraysh gleefully seized on this apparent contradiction, thinking they had outsmarted the Quran. They celebrated, thinking they had found a flaw in the message."
  },
  58: {
    "They exclaimed, 'Which is better: our gods or Jesus?'": "They argued that if Jesus is worshipped and is not condemned, then their idols should also be acceptable. This was a diversionary tactic—they did not actually care about Jesus but used him as a debating tool.",
    "They cite him only to argue": "Their mention of Jesus was not sincere inquiry but mere argumentation for the sake of winning a debate. They had no intention of accepting the truth regardless of the answer.",
    "In fact, they are a people prone to dispute": "Allah exposes their nature—they are quarrelsome, always looking for arguments rather than truth. Such people are not genuinely seeking guidance; they are seeking to confuse and obstruct. This is a warning about engaging with insincere debaters."
  },
  59: {
    "He was only a servant We showed favour to": "Allah clarifies the true status of Jesus (Isa). He was a human being—a servant of Allah—whom Allah honored with prophethood, miracles, and a noble mission. He was not divine, not God's son, but an honored servant. This corrects both the Quraysh's misuse of his example and the Christian doctrine of his divinity.",
    "and made as an example for the Children of Israel": "Jesus was specifically sent as a sign and miracle for the Children of Israel (Bani Israel). His miraculous birth, his ability to heal and raise the dead by Allah's permission, all served as signs to call his people back to true worship of Allah. He was a demonstration of Allah's power, not an object of worship himself."
  },
  60: {
    "Had We willed, We could have easily replaced you all with angels, succeeding one another on earth": "Allah demonstrates His unlimited power. If He wished, He could have created angels to inhabit the earth instead of humans. Humans are not irreplaceable; their existence is a blessing and a test. This humbles human arrogance and reminds us that our role as Allah's vicegerents on earth is a trust, not a right."
  },
  61: {
    "And his second coming is truly a sign for the Hour": "The return of Jesus before the Day of Judgment is mentioned here. His descent to earth near the end of times is one of the major signs of the Hour. The Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) informed us that Jesus will return, kill the false messiah (Dajjal), break the cross (rejecting the false doctrine of crucifixion), and establish justice. This is confirmed in multiple authentic hadiths.",
    "So have no doubt about it": "The Day of Judgment is certain. Jesus' return is certain. These are matters of faith that should not be doubted by believers.",
    "and follow me. This is the Straight Path": "Allah commands following His guidance—the Quran and the way of Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ). This is the straight path that leads to salvation. All other paths lead to deviation and ruin."
  },
  62: {
    "And do not let Satan hinder you": "A clear warning is given to not allow Satan to divert us from the straight path. Satan uses various tactics—doubts, desires, distractions, false arguments—to prevent people from following the truth.",
    "for he is certainly your sworn enemy": "Satan's enmity toward humanity is open and declared. He vowed to mislead humans after being expelled from Paradise. He is not a neutral force or a misunderstood being—he is a clear, open enemy who wants nothing less than our destruction in this life and the next. Knowing this, believers must be vigilant against his whispers and tricks."
  },
  63: {
    "When Jesus came with clear proofs, he declared": "Prophet Isa (Jesus) came to the Children of Israel with undeniable miracles and evidence of his prophethood—healing the blind, curing lepers, and raising the dead by Allah's permission. These clear proofs authenticated his divine mission.",
    "'I have come to you with wisdom'": "Jesus brought divine wisdom—the Gospel (Injeel) and teachings that guided people toward righteousness. His message contained profound guidance for spiritual and moral life, directing people to the worship of One God.",
    "'and to clarify to you some of what you differ about'": "By Jesus' time, the Children of Israel had split into various sects with differing interpretations of religious law. Jesus came to resolve some of these disputes and guide them back to the correct understanding of their religion. He did not come to abolish the law but to clarify it.",
    "'So fear Allah, and obey me'": "This was Jesus' call—consciousness of Allah (Taqwa) and obedience to the messenger. Every prophet delivered this same essential message. Jesus never called people to worship him; he called them to fear Allah and follow his prophetic guidance."
  },
  64: {
    "Surely Allah alone is my Lord and your Lord": "Jesus explicitly declared that Allah is his Lord—he himself was a servant of Allah, not a deity. He placed himself and his followers on equal footing as servants of the same Lord. This verse is a clear refutation of any claim that Jesus is divine or God's son.",
    "so worship Him alone": "The command is unambiguous: worship must be directed to Allah exclusively. Jesus commanded monotheism (Tawheed), the same message brought by every prophet from Adam to Muhammad (ﷺ).",
    "This is the Straight Path": "Worshipping Allah alone is the straight path that leads to Paradise. Any deviation from this—whether worshipping Jesus, saints, idols, or anything else—is a departure from the path that all prophets taught."
  },
  65: {
    "Yet their various groups have differed among themselves about him": "Despite Jesus' clear message, his followers divided into sects after him. Some claimed he was God, others said he was the son of God, others said he was part of a trinity, and some denied him entirely. These divisions arose from human innovation, not from Jesus' teachings.",
    "so woe to the wrongdoers when they face the torment of a painful Day": "Those who distorted Jesus' message and created false doctrines about him will face severe punishment on the Day of Judgment. The term 'wrongdoers' includes all who attributed to Jesus what he never claimed for himself. This is a grave warning about the consequences of religious innovation and distortion."
  },
  66: {
    "Are they waiting for the Hour to take them by surprise when they least expect it?": "This rhetorical question warns the disbelievers and those who distort religion. Are they waiting for the Day of Judgment to come suddenly while they are heedless and unprepared? The Hour will come without warning, catching people in the midst of their daily activities. The wise person prepares now, not waiting until it is too late."
  },
  67: {
    "Close friends will be enemies to one another on that Day": "On the Day of Judgment, friendships based on sin, heedlessness, or worldly interests will turn into bitter enmity. Friends who encouraged each other in wrongdoing will blame each other. Those who bonded over disobedience to Allah will curse one another when they see where their friendship led them.",
    "except the righteous": "Only friendships built on faith, righteousness, and mutual encouragement toward good will endure. The Muttaqeen—those who were conscious of Allah—will remain close friends in the Hereafter because their bond was based on pleasing Allah. This teaches us to choose friends who will benefit us in both worlds. The Prophet (ﷺ) said: 'A person is upon the religion of their close friend, so let each of you look at whom they befriend.' (Tirmidhi)"
  },
  68: {
    "who will be told, 'O My servants! There is no fear for you Today, nor will you grieve'": "Allah will address the righteous with tender words of comfort, calling them 'My servants'—a title of honor. On a Day when terror grips most of humanity, the believers are assured complete security. They will have no fear of what lies ahead and no grief over what they left behind. Every anxiety is removed, replaced by eternal peace."
  },
  69: {
    "those who believed in Our signs and fully submitted to Us": "This verse clarifies who qualifies for this honor. Two conditions are mentioned: belief in Allah's signs (the Quran, the prophets, the miracles, the creation) and complete submission to Allah (Islam). True faith is not merely verbal acknowledgment but wholehearted submission in thought, word, and deed. Those who combined sincere belief with practical obedience are the recipients of this divine reassurance."
  },
  70: {
    "Enter Paradise, you and your spouses, rejoicing": "The believers are invited to enter Paradise along with their righteous spouses. The joy is shared—families reunited in eternal bliss. The word 'rejoicing' (tuhbaroon) indicates a state of supreme happiness, celebration, and delight. Paradise is not a solitary experience but one shared with loved ones who walked the path of faith together."
  },
  71: {
    "Golden trays and cups will be passed around to them": "The people of Paradise will be served in vessels of gold—a luxury forbidden in this world for Muslims but abundantly available in the Hereafter as a reward for their patience and obedience. Servants will circulate with these golden trays and cups, serving the inhabitants of Paradise.",
    "There will be whatever the souls desire and the eyes delight in": "This comprehensive description covers every possible pleasure. Whatever the soul yearns for and whatever brings joy to the eyes will be present. The pleasures of Paradise are beyond human imagination—the Prophet (ﷺ) described it as containing 'what no eye has seen, no ear has heard, and what has never occurred to a human heart.' (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "And you will be there forever": "The greatest gift of all: eternity. Unlike worldly pleasures that end, the delights of Paradise are permanent. There is no fear of death, decline, or expulsion. This eternal nature multiplies every joy infinitely."
  },
  72: {
    "That is the Paradise which you will be awarded for what you used to do": "Paradise is presented as an inheritance earned through righteous deeds. While entry into Paradise is ultimately through Allah's mercy, deeds serve as the means and the measure. Every prayer, act of charity, moment of patience, and good deed performed in the worldly life contributed to this eternal reward. This motivates believers to maximize their good deeds."
  },
  73: {
    "There you will have abundant fruit to eat from": "Paradise contains an endless variety and quantity of fruits. Unlike worldly fruits that are seasonal and limited, the fruits of Paradise are perpetually available, diverse beyond imagination, and satisfying in ways earthly food cannot match. This abundance represents the generosity of Allah toward His righteous servants."
  },
  74: {
    "Indeed, the wicked will be in the torment of Hell forever": "In stark contrast to the believers, the criminals (those who rejected faith and committed grave sins without repentance) will face eternal punishment in Hell. The word 'Mujrimeen' refers to those guilty of crimes against Allah—primarily disbelief and polytheism. Their stay in Hell is not temporary but everlasting, a punishment matching their eternal rejection of truth."
  },
  75: {
    "It will never be lightened for them": "The punishment of Hell will not decrease even slightly. There are no breaks, no relief, no moments of comfort. The intensity remains constant—an eternal torment without any reduction.",
    "and there they will be overwhelmed with despair": "The inhabitants of Hell will be consumed by utter hopelessness. They will realize that there is no escape, no end, no hope. This despair is part of the punishment—knowing that their situation will never improve. This psychological torment compounds the physical suffering."
  },
  76: {
    "We did not wrong them": "Allah declares His perfect justice. He did not punish anyone unfairly. Every person in Hell earned their place through their own choices. Allah sent messengers, revealed books, provided signs, and gave ample time for repentance.",
    "but it was they who were the wrongdoers": "The blame rests entirely on the disbelievers themselves. They wronged themselves by rejecting guidance, persisting in sin, and refusing to repent. They cannot claim injustice because they were given every opportunity to choose differently."
  },
  77: {
    "They will cry, 'O Mâlik! Let your Lord finish us off.'": "In their desperation, the people of Hell will call out to Mâlik, the angel appointed as the guardian of Hell. They will beg for death—for complete annihilation—as an escape from their suffering. They would prefer non-existence over the endless torment they face.",
    "He will answer, 'You are definitely here to stay.'": "Mâlik's response is devastating: there is no death in the Hereafter. They will remain in this state forever. The escape they seek does not exist. This exchange captures the absolute finality and hopelessness of their situation. In a hadith, the Prophet (ﷺ) mentioned that Mâlik will not respond to them for a thousand years, adding to their anguish."
  },
  78: {
    "We certainly brought the truth to you": "Allah reminds them that the truth was delivered to them clearly through prophets, scriptures, and signs. They cannot claim ignorance or say they were not warned. The truth reached them in their worldly life.",
    "but most of you were resentful of the truth": "Most people rejected the truth not because they could not understand it but because they hated it. The truth demanded changes to their lifestyle, challenged their egos, and required submission to Allah. Rather than accept it, they chose to resent and reject it. This resentment of truth is a dangerous spiritual disease that leads to eternal ruin."
  },
  79: {
    "Or have they mastered some evil plan?": "Allah questions the disbelievers who were plotting against the Prophet (ﷺ) and Islam. The Quraysh held secret meetings to devise schemes against the message and the messenger. They thought their plans were hidden and effective.",
    "Then We too are surely planning": "Allah responds that He also has a plan, and His plan always prevails over the plans of humans. When they plotted to harm the Prophet (ﷺ), Allah planned to protect him and make his message triumph. The plots of the Quraysh ultimately failed, and Islam spread throughout the world. This verse reassures believers that no conspiracy against the truth will ultimately succeed."
  },
  80: {
    "Or do they think that We do not hear their evil thoughts and secret talks?": "Do the plotters imagine that their private conversations and hidden schemes are unknown to Allah? Do they think they can hide their true intentions from the All-Hearing, All-Knowing?",
    "Yes We do! And Our messenger-angels are in their presence, recording it all": "Allah emphatically confirms that He hears everything. Moreover, angels are constantly present with every person, recording every word, deed, and even intention. Nothing escapes documentation. On the Day of Judgment, their own records will testify against them. This should instill caution in every person about what they say in private."
  },
  81: {
    "Say, O Prophet, 'If the Most Compassionate really had offspring, I would be the first worshipper.'": "This verse uses a hypothetical statement to make a point. The Prophet (ﷺ) is instructed to say: IF Allah had a son (which He absolutely does not), I would be the first to worship and honor that son—because I am the most devoted servant of Allah. But since Allah has no offspring, such worship would be misguided. This is a rhetorical way of emphasizing that attributing children to Allah is a false claim that the Prophet (ﷺ) completely rejects. It is not a confirmation but a conditional statement showing the absurdity of the claim."
  },
  82: {
    "Glorified is the Lord of the heavens and the earth, the Lord of the Throne": "Allah declares His own transcendence. He is the Lord of the heavens, the earth, and the magnificent Throne—the greatest of all creations. His dominion is absolute and His majesty is beyond comprehension.",
    "far above what they claim": "Allah is completely free from and far above the false attributes they assign to Him—having children, partners, or any need. Their claims are insults to His majesty. He is glorified and exalted beyond their limited, corrupted understanding."
  },
  83: {
    "So let them indulge in falsehood and amuse themselves": "Allah instructs the Prophet (ﷺ) to leave the disbelievers to their idle talk and foolish behavior. They treat religion as a joke and life as a game. Let them continue in their heedlessness—for now.",
    "until they face their Day, which they have been warned of": "Their amusement is temporary. The Day of Judgment is coming, and they have been repeatedly warned about it. When that Day arrives, there will be no more laughter or games. The reality they mocked will become terrifyingly real. This verse provides comfort to the Prophet (ﷺ) and believers: justice will come, even if it seems delayed."
  },
  84: {
    "It is He Who is the only God in the heavens and the only God on the earth": "Allah's divinity extends over all creation—whether in the heavens or on earth. There is no god in any realm except Him. The angels worship Him in the heavens; humans and jinn are commanded to worship Him on earth. His authority is universal and unchallenged.",
    "For He is the All-Wise, All-Knowing": "All of Allah's decrees and actions are based on perfect wisdom (Hakeem) and complete knowledge (Aleem). He knows everything—past, present, and future—and His wisdom ensures that everything He does is perfectly appropriate and purposeful. These attributes distinguish Him from all false gods, who have neither knowledge nor wisdom."
  },
  85: {
    "And Blessed is the One to Whom belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth and everything in between!": "Allah is described as 'Blessed' (Tabaaraka)—possessing unlimited goodness, abundance, and perfection. Everything in existence belongs to Him. His kingdom encompasses every atom in the universe and everything beyond our perception.",
    "With Him alone is the knowledge of the Hour": "Only Allah knows when the Day of Judgment will occur. This knowledge is exclusively His—no angel, prophet, or any creation knows the exact time. The Prophet (ﷺ) was asked about the Hour by Angel Jibreel and replied: 'The one being asked knows no more than the one asking.' (Muslim)",
    "And to Him you will all be returned": "The ultimate destination of every soul is return to Allah. This is a certainty that should guide how we live. Whether we acknowledge Him now or not, we will all stand before Him to be judged."
  },
  86: {
    "But those objects of worship they invoke besides Him have no power to intercede": "The idols, false deities, and objects worshipped besides Allah have absolutely no ability to intercede on behalf of their worshippers on the Day of Judgment. They cannot help themselves, let alone help others. Those who rely on them for intercession will be bitterly disappointed.",
    "except those who testify to the truth knowingly": "The exception refers to righteous beings like angels and prophets who may intercede—but only with Allah's permission and only for those who believed in the truth. Intercession is not automatic or available to everyone; it requires Allah's authorization and the recipient's eligibility through faith. This negates the pagan belief that their idols would advocate for them."
  },
  87: {
    "If you ask them O Prophet who created them, they will certainly say, 'Allah!'": "This returns to a point made earlier in the surah. Even the polytheists, when asked who created them, would acknowledge Allah as the Creator. They did not attribute their existence to their idols.",
    "How can they then be deluded from the truth?": "Given that they acknowledge Allah as their Creator, how can they logically worship anything else? If Allah created them, He alone deserves their worship. Their idolatry is irrational by their own admission. This question exposes the absurdity of polytheism—they already possess the knowledge that should lead them to pure monotheism, yet they remain deluded."
  },
  88: {
    "Allah is Aware of the Prophet's cry: 'O my Lord! Indeed, these are a people who persist in disbelief.'": "Allah acknowledges the Prophet's (ﷺ) complaint and distress over his people's stubborn rejection. The Prophet (ﷺ) called upon his Lord, expressing his grief that despite all his efforts, many of his people refused to believe. This shows the Prophet's (ﷺ) deep concern for his community and his turning to Allah in times of difficulty. Allah heard this cry and responds with guidance."
  },
  89: {
    "So bear with them and respond with peace": "Allah advises the Prophet (ﷺ) to be patient with the disbelievers and to respond to their hostility with peace—not aggression or bitterness. The word 'Safh' implies turning away gracefully, not harboring resentment. Saying 'Salaam' (peace) maintains dignity and does not engage in their foolishness. This was the prophetic way—meeting ignorance with grace.",
    "They will soon come to know": "A final warning is issued. The disbelievers will eventually learn the truth of what they rejected—either through defeat in this world or punishment in the Hereafter. The phrase carries both a promise and a threat. For those who later accepted Islam, they came to know the truth and found salvation. For those who persisted in denial until death, they discovered the reality of the Hereafter firsthand. The surah ends with this sobering reminder that the truth will prevail, and everyone will ultimately face the consequences of their choices."
  }
};